U.S.: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It’s funny how Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, which he considered to be the dumbest.
When he finally debunked his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had written it over a copy machine from Bush’s Iraqi script three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase “as in Iraq” several times in the text itself, but he did not even hesitate to use the name of Bush’s January 2007 statement as the name of his own declaration: “A New Way Forward.”
Three years ago, he criticized Bush’s idea of sending fresh military forces to Iraq, suffering from the civil war, as “irresponsible and, in its aftermath, catastrophic.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of the field commanders, was the only one possible and so successful that there is no talk of Iraq in the news sessions today.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, but objectively left his successor in a much more grateful starting position than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
He was again requested by field commanders, in particular Afghanistan’s Operation Commander General Stanley McCristal, who, despite subordinate customs, harshly criticized the hesitant gunmen in the White House.
He asked 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he could not think of anything better, and so at least he dressed the general by 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to squeeze another 5,000 promises out of Europe, even though he initially counted at least 10.
The most problematic of the entire Obama strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to end this process in three years. The entire Obama doctrine raises more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a half-increase will bear the same fruit as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal war of recent years, the Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honoring the agreements.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the opposite symptom - no one can be trusted and no agreements are observed.
Under these conditions, the Afghan security forces, accustomed every day to changing their masters as they see fit, are preparing poorly.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain only a village in Timor-Leste for which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily difficult given the opaque conditions that further complicate Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the construction of an "accessible state", which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, does not seem too realistic.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is striking with its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of an explosion.
To believe that soldiers sent into a war rage for the purpose of "quickly returning home" will cause the miracle done here, can only the soul truly romantic, untouched by reality.
From a political point of view, it is irresponsible to set a date for the withdrawal of troops, as the Taliban will perceive it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit has shown that Europeans’ willingness to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is declining.
European politicians do not know and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically intervening in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions do not affect Iran, the question before the United States is whether or not to try to solve the problem by military force.
It will be necessary to respond to it just at a time when, according to Obama, America is stepping up to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also mean a dramatic reversal in the Afghan situation.
The only plaque for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left before the presidential election, and therefore there is still enough time left for him to come up with another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
