The work of experts from the three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from the University of Science and Technology in Prague and from the University of Heidelberg paves the way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metallocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new ‘improved’ compounds prepared based on knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metallocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Treacherous and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by HIV cleavage, there would be no ripe infectious virus particles.
When we stop HIV protease, we will also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is further systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in the tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from patients infected with HIV.
The effect of metallocarboranes on the normal variant of the enzyme is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
