The UDF raises the tone and urges the Nouveau Centre party not to continue using their abbreviation.
The UDF, controlled by MoDemFran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Bayrou, on Friday reacted to an attempt by Nouveau Centre president Hervé Morin to take over the former Giscardo party by not using the abbreviation in any media under threat of prosecution.
Hervé Morin has publicly announced his intention to acquire the abbreviation UDF with the fact that Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Bayrou does not deserve to bear its legacy after he handed his hand to the left.
The Minister of Defense, whose party is a partner of the UMP, planned to confirm this strategy on Saturday in front of the National Council of the Nouveau Centre (NC).
This step was supported by the MP Hervé de Charett (former pro-UMP now for NC), who ascribes ownership to the UDF brand, as he was the first to have it registered with the National Institute of Industrial Property (l'Institut national de la propriété industrielle) in 2004.
But on Friday night, a UDF committee headed by Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Bayrou’s friends, who do not intend to be evicted, stepped down from their silence and formally requested the minister and lawmakers to stop using the abbreviation and hand over ownership of the trademark, under the threat of criminal prosecution.
In recent days, you have raised alarming statements that you will propose to your political movement to retake the abbreviation UDF, writes the Association in its letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the committee, including Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez of the MoDem Centre or Senator Jean Arthui.
At the same time, you considered it appropriate to place on your promotional materials and on the welcome website of your movement the name + Nouveau centre+, with the slogan +UDF today +, the signatories of the letter also state.
As you are aware, you have no right to use this abbreviation, the UDF committee explains, requesting the NC movement "immediately remove all UDF name mentions from all promotional materials, including (its) websites".
At the same time, it asks Hervé de Charette "to transfer the ownership of the trademark to the legitimate owners".
If you do not do so, we will turn to the courts to respect the law and the legitimate rights of UDF members, the signatories note.
In their letter, they state that the UDF "has been a full-fledged political movement since 1978" and recall that Mr. Morin and his friends "elected" a departure in 2007, "to create a competitive movement, like others in 2002, to found the UMP.
According to them, the Nouveau centre has no right to use the abbreviation UDF (Union pour la démocratie fran<0xC3><0xA7>aise).
At the same time, they recall that the last UDF Congress voted in 2007 to join MoDem for three years and to create a committee to defend the "moral and material interests" of the association founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, the committee continues, "when he registered the trademark," he was "not a member of the UDF for three years", but of the UMP.
In a scandalous and fraudulent way, he used the non-existent registration of an acronym to do so on his own account.
This inattentiveness begins to turn into a crime, they declare, and then ironically they express themselves to the NC strategy: "It seems to us that in both politics and ordinary life it is more valuable to create a name for yourself than to withdraw from anonymity by fraudulently adopting a name that has no name."
Liliane Bettencourt’s case: Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois-Marie Banier will be tried for abuse of a state of weakness.
A Nanterre court on Friday decided to sue artist Fran<0xC3><0xA7>oise-Marie Banier and make a verdict on whether he used the 80-year-old billionaire’s state of weakness to strip her of part of her fortune, for which her daughter Liliane Bettencourt blamed him.
