It’s been two years since Liliana Bettencourt’s only daughter began criminal proceedings against Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois-Marie Banier, a photographer and all-rounder who she blames for years of using her mother’s state of infirmity to get a gift of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 billion in checks, life insurance contracts or paintings.
But Liliane Bettencourt has always denied being manipulated by a photographer she considers a long-term friend.
While the court had to assess the validity of the lawsuit filed by Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers’ Friday court speech had at times turned into a family hour of truth.
Liliana Bettencourt’s lawyer submitted three letters to her notary in 1999, 2003 and 2005, expressing her distrust of her husband, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>oise Bettencourt-Meyers.
In a 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt adds, “You could explain to my daughter that I have been writing to Banier for fifteen years once or twice a day.
Ever since she got married, I have never been able to talk to Fran<0xC3><0xA7>oise."
The Nanterre Public Prosecutor’s Office again found that the complainant’s conduct was not justified, all the more so when the guardian judge in those days rejected her application to initiate proceedings to issue legal protection for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "is fully capable of participating in court, not under protection or guardianship.
No one else will act for her," prosecutor Marie-Christine Daubigney said.
Finally, the Court decided that Ms Bettencourt-Meyers's case would be heard at the time of the opening of the proceedings.
Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
Unless anything changes in the management of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence was futile...
For more than a decade, the behaviour of management of large companies towards employees has been reminiscent of the approach of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of employees identifying themselves with "values" determined from the mountain, as it was before when it was necessary to impose on consumers the products that came out of the attack.
By becoming the center of business companies, the marketing revolution has aligned the strategy of conquering the market in the right direction... although authoritarian efforts to impose products, different from customer preferences, come back regularly!
The passive attitude of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault companies are only a visible part of a much more widespread general phenomenon that affects mainly management staff.
This demobilization adversely affects the development of all the intellectual functions of society, including research and development, and more importantly, economic intelligence.
And indeed, the EI “requires all stakeholders (...) to have an active approach and the ability to foresee” and demands from employees commitments that are completely at odds with the revenues of authoritarian management.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that aims to put employees at the center of the interest of the company as well as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls.
Will internal opinion polls - like a questionnaire submitted to Orange employees - contribute to a revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
Mainly because I have already convinced myself that in the face of a new situation, the structure will return to what it has always done after various detours!
Moreover, authoritarianism, as one of the pathologies of power, increases in proportion to the severity of one’s own failures.
And finally, because most managers have a simplified view of human behavior.
Because they are graduates of colleges for engineers, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
For the sake of convenience of thought, they adopt an old behaviorist theory, currently revived by the "neuroscience" of the United States and widely disseminated without much knowledge by scientific institutes and the media.
With the "sic" involvement of managers being possible, a recent survey by Ipsos showed on Figaro.fr, which only strengthens managers in their position of mechanical control, unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors.
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes the adoption of the final vision of human behavior.
It consists in incorporating basic insight into all management intentions and practices: For employees, commitments to the company will only be possible if they appear as a clear means to achieve their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Currently, this concept of employee motivation is only concerned with the study of Motivational Functional Analysis.
These studies have shown that they evaluate their businesses on the basis of predefined doxy, which allows them, through an image that tells about the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life goals.
By identifying and measuring these mobilization factors, managers can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and put their human resource management “on track”.
This creates a breeding ground for the development of sound and effective economic intelligence.
