Turkish justice has dissolved for the Kurdish side, and this decision has serious consequences.
The Turkish Constitutional Court on Friday ruled to abolish the main pro-Kurdish party in the country. This decision immediately sparked protests in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision can greatly complicate the task of the government, which is trying to give the Kurdish community a friendly hand and try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) has been dissolved because it has become "a hub of activities that threaten the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Supreme Court Chairman Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of negotiations.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, when a majority of seven votes was needed to dissolve the party, Kili<0xC3><0xA7> said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president Ahmet Türk and MEP Aysela Tuglukova, were banned from participating in political life for five years.
At the same time, the judge announced the lifting of parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr Türk and Mrs Tuglukova and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP party has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 500).
The party’s leadership has already warned before the verdict that MPs would rather leave Parliament than act as MPs without political authority.
The decision is a continuation of the process initiated in 2007 by the Prosecutor of the Court of Cassation, Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses the DTP of obedience to the "commands" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider to be a terrorist organization.
Many observers are convinced that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party says it has no "basic connection" to the PKK, but refuses to label it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The verdict comes as the government lends a friendly hand to the Kurdish community and offers a number of measures to strengthen their rights and tries to limit the support of the Kurds for the PKK to end the conflict.
The DTP leadership confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to a resumption of tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where in recent weeks many demonstrations have erupted against the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah <0xC3><0x96>calan is detained in clashes with police.
Since the announcement of the justice decision, thousands of demonstrators have gathered in front of the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast that is inhabited mostly by Kurds.
Police used tear grenades and water cannons, and demonstrators threw Molotov cocktails or fired stones from washing machines.
About 100 people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said that the decision of justice only "prolongs desperation".
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (the Kurds, note red.) by banning the party, he said in the press.
The government, made up of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also condemned the decision.
We are on the principle of non-disruption of the parties.
It doesn’t solve anything, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision is a complete rejection of the democratic proposals launched by the government, commented political scientist Ahmet Insel.
Of course, we can expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK reported one of the deadliest attacks in northern Turkey, which killed seven soldiers three days earlier.
