The Cradle of Dinosaurs
The Tawa Hallae looked like a lot of other carnivorous dinosaurs: The animal, two meters long and 1.50 meters high, ran along two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short front limbs with swollen claws.
If this species lived a few million years later, there would be nothing extraordinary.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's issue of Science writes that Tawa Hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in the equator arid region of the supercontinent Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window to the earlier evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about relationships, expansions, and signs of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavations at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
“Sometimes we found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for triassic sediments,” said team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
The finding confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god Hopi.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are very rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
This finding is not particularly sensational, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are not complete, so the attribution of pradinosaurs is usually controversial.
Experts discuss, for example, when lizards split into three main lines of development: carnivorous theropods, to which later belonged Tyranosaurus rex, Velociraptor and also birds, "long-necked" four-legged sauropods such as the lizards and their relatives, and the herbivorous orchid.
After analyzing Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa Hallae is the original terapod.
It exhibits an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa Hallae, for example, researchers found evidence of air sacs that even the descendants of theropod birds have.
Thanks to air sacs, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa Hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the relative lineage of the giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light bones, this useful innovation has probably already created a common ancestor of both groups.
At least three waves of migration into North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists have concluded that lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three lines of development split early and spread from South America to all the continents that then formed a unified Earth mass as the supercontinent Pangea.
She would also speak for the fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
These three cannot come from one common, migrated ancestor, the scientists argue.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration into North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the scientific study.
Of course, there are contradictions as well.
One even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His assumption could put together a distorted picture, because in South America, a lot of primitive dinosaur fossils have been preserved, with other continents rarely found.
As dinosaurs have proven that they evolved from a relatively rare lineage of reptiles to the dominant vertebrates of the earth in the Middle Ages, it remains a riddle.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and flying lizards and countless other lizards.
Around the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread throughout the world and many new species evolved, while relatives died out and interfaced the Triassic and Jurassic.
The success story didn’t last forever.
There are two hypotheses on how to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction, which the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs adapted better, so they could outshine the competition.
However, the success story didn’t last forever.
150 million years later, the impact of the meteorite helped another group of animals, which also evolved into the Triassic and has since lived in the shadows: mammals.
