Like a dream, psychosis opens up a flood of thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, Chief Physician of the General Psychiatry Clinic of the University Clinic in Heidelberg.
Schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, becomes, like in a dream, overcome by events and cannot actively form them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
Comparison with reality is usually not possible with them, ghosts are a terrible reality, awakening is excluded.
Having a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchss says, "but the sensory and spatial structure of the reality that one perceives in psychosis remains fundamentally preserved."
Blurred thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in a real framework.
Scientists are still puzzled as to why our brains are doing this kind of stuff.
Exceptional states can cause any person to lose their relationship to reality in the short term, says Fuchs.
Not everyone develops into psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Scientists believe that the affected individuals have minimal brain damage.
We believe that in the early stages of development there will be damage to the neuronal maturation of the brain, for example, by the mother's viral disease during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
However, it remains a riddle as to how the neural system, which has not manifested itself in any way for many years, will malfunction.
The influences of the environment also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the trigger of psychosis, if there is a disposition to it.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmission system.
<0xE2><0x99><0xAA> When our brains are boiling <0xE2><0x99><0xAA>
It’s crazy that psychotronics suffer from their hallucinations, and to get rid of them, they swallow expensive drugs, others give money for drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten from Lübeck.
Whether we perceive delusions as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a question of attitude.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and delusions for ten years, last year he interpreted his results in the book "Die unreale Welt in unserem Kopf" (The unreal world in our head).
Although hallucinations belong to the typical accompanying phenomena of psychoses, but also to surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline personality or depression, diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s or brain trauma are also common.
Surprisingly, it also hallucinates the brain of a healthy person under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of the contents of thoughts that are normally suppressed.
They arise when the parts of the brain in which sensory perception is processed are too active or under-suppressed; when our brain slows down, or when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the removal of stimuli, stress, worries with love or other exceptional conditions.
In recent studies, up to one-third of respondents reported having hallucinated at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attending high school there.
Actually, she's a perfectly normal girl.
If it weren't for the shapes and the voices.
During breaks, she may be approached by a spinal cord with long, dark hair.
When she answers, her classmates look at her with surprise - no one but her sees and hears this boy.
This daring girl thinks of herself as a tenacious dreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't, she knows.
He wakes up, hears and sees the boy, just as he hears and sees the girl sitting next to him on the bench.
He can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? he asks sometimes.
But he knows that this boy and other delusions are not real and will disappear again.
At night, the sights are rather daunting.
Frequently, delusions are a burden.
When she sits in class, she cannot watch the lesson many times, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is just presenting a new classmate, while he explains to everyone else audibly and visibly on the table of the mathematical equation.
At night, the appearances are rather depressing.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which comes rarely and too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or if she is already asleep, whether the images she sees, the grimaces, or the girl with bleeding cuts on her hands and feet arise in front of her open or behind her.
Leave me alone, she's yelling at the characters.
She doesn't tell her parents and friends about it, they'd think she'd gone crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She graduated last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she contacted Kasten on the internet, she knows she hasn't gone crazy.
Deception is also an art of desperation.
If someone is socially isolated or is deprived of stimuli, they are more likely to have hallucinations, Kasten says.
I think the brain doesn’t have enough work and takes care of its own fun.
Sarah K., the only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she had been calling her father from the time she was thinking was not her own father.
Because in visual and acoustic hallucinations, the same brain regions that also process real sensations and sounds are active, it is difficult for those affected like Sarah K. to distinguish delusion and reality from each other. "Every experience," says Kasten, "is played out in the brain, also reality is played out there.
Hallucinations are also images that allow the brain to form, which is why they act so realistically.”
Also, night dreams are evaluated by Kasten as a form of hallucination.
The hallucination of healthy people is not fundamentally different from the hallucination in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to evaluate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
The Borderline Between Sleep and Hallucination
Unfortunately, in our world too focused on consciousness, the imaginary experience is mostly pathological, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and head of the Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic at Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, suffering disease, but it also brings positives, creativity - delusion is also an art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of altered consciousness to dream.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictional dreams that the person concerned considers to be real and cannot even distinguish them retrospectively from the waking state.
The oneiroid state of consciousness occurs in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example, patients with polyradicular inflammation, who experience motor disease with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and himself, perhaps by a permanent, complete inability to move, he replaces a life threatening a real situation with his own imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline state between dreaming and hallucination.
Because in reality it is not possible to cope with a situation, the worlds will change, but the real situation will be present in the imagination.
An intense form of supporting the senses and translating the senses into some unbearable situation, which allows us to pass through our own ability to form in a moment into a loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in the memories
Also, art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a saving act of the soul.
He was 49 years old when, after heart valve surgery and subsequent heart transplantation, his consciousness was released on a several-day trip, his body lying motionless on an intensive care unit.
Claussen immersed himself in the world he created, visited foreign times and places: he becomes an old man tied to a bed, in a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility, who produce narcotic substances from blood.
On a motorcycle, he is taken by a Greek to his homeland, on a hospital bed he surfs the firn in the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
It is completely immersed in imaginary events, everything is real, even later in memories.
These inner paths are fundamentally different for Clausen from any dream.
A dream is a different state, it describes its experience.
Contrary to dreams, the memories of those mental journeys are still clear after years and in trivial details.
Even brighter and more intense than the actual experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other true experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, oneiroid states, psychoses, hallucinations and drug entanglements show how fragile even in the waking state our inner images of external realities are.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up psychologist Kasten, "can lead to the deformation of what we call reality."
A fact that can also be enriching.
