75% of working mothers have work-related problems related to motherhood.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who are planning to have a child.
This is the result of a study 'Fertility and the working career of Spanish women', conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 years and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labor market due to maternity.
The study highlights that at the beginning of the partnership, there are many differences in views on the number of children, depending on whether they work or not, and also by type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with a partner earlier, have their first child earlier and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, delay coexistence and maternity, and have fewer offspring.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years from the start of cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving their stable employment and therefore had to postpone cohabitation and the arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on motherhood, although it has a minor influence on the time of starting cohabitation with a partner," explains Margarita Delgado, who is researching at CSIC.
Another factor influencing the age of women at the time of marriage is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women marry and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35 to 49 years, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with basic education marry and give birth to their first child before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education progress on the contrary prefer to get a stable job, before getting married and giving birth to their first child," says Delgado.
