The auxiliary system for the manual brake is already a mandatory equipment.
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock system, with ESP stability control, auxiliary handbrake systems, all this will become the mandatory equipment of European cars.
In fact, it is already part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the others a deadline is set for eliminating the deficiency, which is February 2011.
The measure introduced in the EU aims to increase the protection of pedestrians, while working in a way that can help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary handbrake system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects after the driver has stepped down.
But he can’t always hold that pressure to the end.
According to a study carried out by the auto parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers who have an accident did not get off the brakes before the crash, and half of them did not use the full force of the brakes.
Up to 1,100 accidents
Conversely, this assistance requires the braking system to the maximum, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related fatalities could be prevented annually.
Reducing this number will be even more marked—according to calculations, it would prevent one in four accidents with an impact on people—after the introduction of so-called smart handbrake systems.
In this case, vehicles will be equipped with a system that (using radar or cameras) captures obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help him to increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if the collision cannot be prevented, the device will impact the brake as intensely as possible and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
